Fu Hao is a spiritual leader and powerful general who mixes a strong army with a balanced economy. She uses a combination of vegetable farms and pig farms to boost her popularity and weapons workshops to create an army of auxiliary and imperial troops. Any leftover weapons are sold for gold to boost her treasury. This is complemented with a well-defended castle, reinforcing Fu Hao's reputation as a formidable all-round opponent.

Genghis Khan favours a nomadic lifestyle and maintains only a humble castle. His village economy is designed around generating gold, needed to train his favourite fighting troop, the horse archer. The swiftness of his horse archers is perfect for quick hit and run attacks on his enemies.

Hideyoshi is the most sophisticated of all the rulers. His impressive castle complements a well developed economy featuring both silk and tea production. His expert understanding of the way of the ninja can catch his enemies off-guard and his warrior monks allow for swift, decisive attacks. Hideyoshi's long-term goal, however, is to build an army of samurai warriors.

Kublai Khan is a wise and methodical adversary. He favors a simple agricultural economy, focused on rice production, but uses tea and clothing to boost his popularity amongst his people. His weapons workshops specialize in heavy weapons. These powerful troops stand alongside mounted units and a variety of siege equipment to form a formidable well-balanced army.

Qin Shi Huang is slow, methodical and ruthless. His economy is well developed with silk production complementing his food farms. Although he uses auxiliary units to establish an army, his aim is to build a powerful force of imperial troops to crush his opponents.

Qin Shi Huang is slow, methodical and ruthless. His economy is well developed with silk production complementing his food farms. Although he uses auxiliary units to establish an army, his aim is to build a powerful force of imperial troops to crush his opponents.

Sun Tzu is a master tactician who favours playing the long game. His economy is built around the production of specific weapon types needed to train powerful troops, with any excess sold for profit. This efficiency extends to his castle that remains compact but well defended. His offensive style is methodical, well thought out and deadly.

Thuc Phan prefers to concentrate on agriculture, running his economy using basic food farms. Early on he relies on tribesmen to form his army but will eventually turn to auxiliary units as his economy grows. Thuc Phan likes to attack early to disrupt the progress of his enemies.

Minamoto no Yoritomo is a noble traditionalist. His basic economy is simple, dominated by rice and meat. To supplement this Yoritomo prefers to play good lord and uses temples and tea houses to boost his popularity. His army is built for speed with warrior monks and archers, supported by cavalry, preferred to slow, heavy troops.

Warlords can be influenced diplomatically using Influence Points which are bought with Diplomacy Points. Once the diplomatic capture threshold has been reached, a player can capture the Warlord.


Players can use the +10 Influence button (cost: 20 Diplomacy Points) or +20 Influence button (cost: 50 Diplomacy Points) to build influence. Alternatively, the Auto button adds +10 Influence (cost: 20 Diplomacy Points) every 10 seconds.


The influence circle displays the total number of Influence Points each player has used to influence the Warlord. The inner circle represents the diplomatic capture threshold. The number of points required to reach each Warlord's threshold is displayed under the influence circle.


Once a player has reached the capture threshold, the Demand Obedience button becomes available and the Warlord can be captured.


The new owner can add more Influence Points to increase the capture threshold but these will decay over time. A rival player can steal the Warlord by exceeding the capture threshold.

The major benefit of using the market to buy and sell food, resources and weapons is that you can use the market's autobuy and autosell tools. The tools allow you to set a level at which the market will automatically buy or sell individual food items, resources and weapons on your behalf.


For example if you always want to have 10 swords in your armoury, set the autobuy slider for swords to 10. When the number of swords in your armoury drops below 10 the market will automatically buy enough swords to bring the level back up to 10.


If, however, you are making more stone than you need, set the autobuy slider for stone to 100. As soon as you exceed 100 stone stored in the stockpile, the market will sell the excess stone.

Changing your peasants' food rationing is one of the quickest ways to influence your {popularity}.


Rice is the most important food ration as it is the only one that peasants need to be happy. Running out of rice will result in your peasants becoming unhappy which will negatively affect your popularity.


If you really want to make your peasants happy you can provide them with vegetable, meat and tea rations on top of your rice rations. There is no negative hit for running out of vegetables, meat or tea.


A {TeaHouse} is required if you wish to set tea rations.


If you have a surplus of food you may want to consider increasing your food rations further to help boost your popularity.

On the {warlords_map} you can spend Diplomacy points to influence individual {warlords}, allowing you to capture them diplomatically. Militaries, fortifications, and great distances can be bypassed entirely with skilled diplomacy, forcing warlords to pledge their loyalty and abilities to you. Powerful allies can be plucked directly from your enemies' control and made to serve you instead.


Clicking on a warlord you do not currently control opens the Influence panel.


Each player's current influence with the warlord is shown, along with the threshold amount required to begin a diplomatic capture. This threshold is different for each type of warlord.


Buttons on the Influence panel allow you to convert your pool of Diplomacy Points into Influence Points for the selected Warlord. Clicking +10 or +20 will spend Diplomacy Points to gain that much Influence. There is a small cooldown period before your administration can do it again. You can click the Auto button to automatically apply the +10 Influence button at every cooldown until the capture threshold is reached.


Once your Influence points for the warlord reach the capture threshold, you can click the Demand Obedience button to carry out a diplomatic capture. Once it succeeds, the warlord is yours to command with Edicts. (See: {IssuingEdicts})


NOTE: If the owner of a Warlord has spent enough diplomacy points to reach the maximum influence level then another player cannot take control of the Warlord until the owner's influence drops below the maximum level.

To build the market, click on the market icon in the town buildings panel.


A market can be vital in oiling the wheels of your castle economy. Along with taxing your population, selling goods is the only other way to generate gold.


The market allows you to buy and sell all goods from a single location. Clicking on the market will bring up the trading panel. On it, you can view the goods the traders are offering before deciding what you wish to buy or sell.


The market also features some advanced buying and selling tools not available in the {stockpile}, {granary} and {armoury}. For each type of good, you can use sliders to specify automatic buy and sell quantities. The market will buy or sell goods to hold your stocks within the specified range, if possible, allowing you to concentrate on other areas of your economy.

Popularity is one of the most important factors in running your economy as it allows you to control various aspects such as peasant migration, {taxation} rate and {foodrationing}.


The number displayed at the top of the Popularity Information panel shows your overall popularity. This represents the total of all the popularity factors listed below it. Click on overall popularity to open the Popularity Information dropdown.


Popularity is the determining factor of how fast peasants arrive or leave your castle. Being a popular ruler will encourage peasants from outside the castle to come and work at the castle. The more popular you are the faster they will come. However, if you are an unpopular lord then people will be unhappy and will leave the castle.


By increasing or decreasing the individual popularity factors you can determine the exact speed in which peasants arrive at or leave the castle.


Although having a high popularity rating is needed to quickly bring peasants to your castle, there are times when you may not want to be so popular. If, for example, you need to raise gold then you will need to set your taxes very high. This will be very unpopular with your population and will have a negative effect on your popularity.


Using the popularity information panel, however, allows you to offset that negative effect by possibly increasing {foodrationing} or {ClothesRationing}. So while you maybe unpopular for imposing very high taxes, the peasants will enjoy your generous food rations, allowing you to still maintain an overall positive popularity. This is particularly useful when a negative event is taking place, since events are out of your control but their effects can be minimised through clever use of other popularity factors.

To build a temple, click one of the temple icon in the town buildings panel.


Every work building (i.e. buildings that require a worker) and house within the radius of a temple generates a {spirit} point. Additional spirit points can be generated by connecting Roads from the Keep to Temples, and from the Grasshopper Warlord's perk. The popularity bonus is then based on the proportion of spirit points against the total number of houses and work buildings.


There are 6 temples with increasing areas of spiritual coverage. If all your buildings are within the radius of a temple, then all your peasants are spiritually enlightened and you will receive the maximum popularity bonus.

Harnessing the ancient principles of the sling and the lever at a grand scale, the Trebuchet can deliver heavy rocks at a high trajectory over great distances. While less accurate than the {catapult}, it has much larger range and can be devastating against walls while sitting well out of harm's way. Peasants may scoff at this engineering marvel, but you'll have the last laugh when their fortified castle is filled with diseased animal gibblets.


The trebuchet has two forms: packed and unpacked. When packed, it may be moved on wheels to bring it into range of its target. Once there, it can be unpacked using the 'unit orders' panel, allowing it to be fired. Trebuchets are very vulnerable to enemy footsoldiers and thus should be carefully guarded.


In addition to rocks, Trebuchets also have the special ability to throw thunder crash bombs and diseased animals. Thunder crash bombs cause firey explosions on contact. Hurling dead animals over enemy walls causes the spread of disease amongst your enemy’s population, disrupting their economy. Each type of ammo has its own cooldown before it can be used again.

The whirling dervish is a very unique mercenary. He has a rechargable sprint which is perfect for swift surprise attacks. Once into the fight, the dervish launches into a whirl of spinning swords allowing him to do great damage to groups of units. This makes him particularly useful against groups of lightly armoured units, such as archers. Beware though, the dervish does not wear armour himself so some well placed arrows or a few blows from a sword will strike him down.


Special Ability: {SprintAttack}, {AreaAttack}
